Goals of the course

By the end of the semester, you should be able to:

  • Define contentious politics and identify the major motivating questions and key theories in the field.

  • Critically assess the methods and major data sources for studying contentious politics and have a sound understanding of their strengths and weaknesses.

  • Collect, clean, and analyze data on contentious politics to produce original research on a real-world instance of contentious political behavior.

Required Materials

  • Additional readings/data provided through ELMS or github

What is contentious politics?

Contentious politics

  • Coordinated claims-making that impinges on someone elseâs interest

  • Must be:

    • Collective
    • Deliberate
    • Political (involves government as a target or audience, but not as the primary actor)
    • At least some non-institutional component

Defining the scope

  • Originates with research on protests and social movementsâ¦but!

  • Social movements are considered one of several tools in the âcontentious repertoireâ

17th century contention

Social movements as historically contingent

Contentious politics is universal but:

  • Precursors to social movements were more parochial, concerned immediate local interests, worked by direct influence (public humiliation, destruction of property, physical pain, or state overthrow)

  • Social movements are tied to the emergence of liberal democracy, industrialization and an urban middle class, and the consolidation of nation-states with centralized bureaucracies.

  • They donât happen everywhere, and they might eventually become as archaic as chivaree

  • Social movements belong to a class of actions that also includes: strikes, riots, terrorism, revolutions etc.

Problems, methods, and themes

Collective Action Problem(s)

  • Olson: the demand for collective action will generally exceed the supply

    • Contentious actors face a Free-Rider problem (why?)
    • Overcoming it typically requires organization and resources

Contentious Interaction

  • Contentious politics involves groups with disparate interests

  • Contentious politics takes place in a social/political/economic context

  • Contentious politics involves governments and is shaped by interactions with authorities

Temporal and spatial patterns

Contentious actions come in waves

Identities, interests and frames

  • Collective actors share identities or they work to form one

  • Even if we can solve the free rider problem, we need to agree on what to do, who we are, who we represent, and who we oppose

Research Methods

  • Some similarities in research methods across issue areas:

    • Event catalogs
    • Organizational ecology, network analysis
    • Surveys and individual biographies
    • Process tracing, comparative methods
